        <section class="main-section" id="Introduction_to_Python">
            <header>Introduction to Python</header>
            <p>Python is a high-level, interpreted, and general-purpose programming language. Its design philosophy emphasizes code readability with its notable use of significant whitespace.</p>
            <p>It provides constructs that enable clear programming on both small and large scales. To output text to the console, you use a simple built-in function.</p>
            <pre><code>print("Hello, World!")</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section class="main-section" id="Variables_and_Data_Types">
            <header>Variables and Data Types</header>
            <p>In Python, variables do not need explicit declaration to reserve memory space. The declaration happens automatically when you assign a value to a variable.</p>
            <p>The equal sign (<code>=</code>) is used to assign values to variables. Python has various standard data types used to define the operations possible on them.</p>
            <pre><code>age = 25
name = "Alice"
is_developer = True</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section class="main-section" id="Control_Flow">
            <header>Control Flow</header>
            <p>Python relies on indentation (using whitespace) to define the scope of loops, conditionals, and functions. Other programming languages often use curly-brackets for this purpose.</p>
            <p>The <code>if</code> statement is used for conditional execution. You can combine it with <code>elif</code> and <code>else</code> blocks to control the flow of execution based on conditions.</p>
            <pre><code>if age >= 18:
    print("Eligible to vote")
else:
    print("Not eligible to vote")</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section class="main-section" id="Functions">
            <header>Functions</header>
            <p>A function is a block of organized, reusable code that is used to perform a single, related action. Functions provide better modularity for your application and a high degree of code reusing.</p>
            <p>You can define functions to provide the required functionality. You use the keyword <code>def</code> followed by the function name and parentheses to create a function.</p>
            <pre><code>def greet(user_name):
    return f"Hello, {user_name}!"</code></pre>
        </section>

        <section class="main-section" id="Lists_and_Loops">
            <header>Lists and Loops</header>
            <p>Lists are one of the 4 built-in data types in Python used to store collections of data. They are created using square brackets and can contain mixed data types.</p>
            <p>A <code>for</code> loop is used for iterating over a sequence (that is either a list, a tuple, a dictionary, a set, or a string).</p>
            <pre><code>fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
for fruit in fruits:
    print(fruit)</code></pre>
            
            <p>Key collection types in Python include:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Lists:</strong> Ordered and changeable. Allows duplicate members.</li>
                <li><strong>Tuples:</strong> Ordered and unchangeable. Allows duplicate members.</li>
                <li><strong>Sets:</strong> Unordered, unchangeable, and unindexed. No duplicate members.</li>
                <li><strong>Dictionaries:</strong> Ordered and changeable. No duplicate members.</li>
                <li><strong>Strings:</strong> Arrays of bytes representing unicode characters.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

